1. Understanding the Issue:
EarlyCSE crashes when attempting to CSE two calls to the commutative intrinsic llvm.smin.i32 that differ in their call site attribute sets (one has the strictfp attribute, the other does not). The crash occurs in combineIRFlags(), specifically at the assertion that attribute intersection must succeed for callsites that were considered identical earlier in the pass.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The debug log shows: EarlyCSE CSE:   %call2 ... to: %call ... #1 meaning EarlyCSE decided the second intrinsic call (%call2) is redundant and should be replaced by the first (%call). This decision precedes combineIRFlags(), which tries to merge IR flags and callsite attributes. The assertion failure indicates the earlier equivalence test allowed matching of these two calls even though their attributes cannot be intersected.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
Looking at EarlyCSE.cpp, equality for value numbering relies on DenseMapInfo<SimpleValue>::isEqualImpl(). For non-identical instructions, special cases allow commuted equality: lines 396–404 contain logic for commutative intrinsics:

if (LII && RII && LII->getIntrinsicID() == RII->getIntrinsicID() && LII->isCommutative() && LII->arg_size() >= 2) {
  return LII->getArgOperand(0) == RII->getArgOperand(1) && ... }

This branch ignores callsite attributes entirely. Thus two commutative intrinsic calls with mismatched attributes are treated as equal. Later, combineIRFlags() assumes (via the assert) that any calls deemed identical have attribute sets that can be intersected; it invokes tryIntersectAttributes(To <- From). For our reproducer the first path (normal identical check) fails due to differing attributes; then the commutative intrinsic path returns true based only on operands, so equality succeeds. However attribute intersection later fails, triggering the assertion. Therefore the invariant “calls judged equal must have intersectable attributes” is broken specifically for the commutative intrinsic fallback.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
Modify the commutative intrinsic equality branch in isEqualImpl (lines 396–404) to also verify that the attribute sets can be intersected (same test used in hasSameSpecialState / Instruction::hasSameSpecialState for calls when IntersectAttrs=true). If the intersection fails, return false instead of treating the instructions as equal. This restores the invariant assumed by combineIRFlags(). Concretely, insert an attribute intersection check before returning true in the commutative intrinsic block:

Pseudo-diff:
--- before
if (LII && RII && ... ) {
  return operands_commute_match && other_args_match;
}
--- after
if (LII && RII && ... ) {
  if (!LII->getAttributes().intersectWith(LII->getContext(), RII->getAttributes()).has_value())
    return false;
  return operands_commute_match && other_args_match;
}

This change ensures calls with non-intersectable attribute sets (like differing strictfp presence if that cannot be intersected) are not CSE'd, avoiding the assertion in combineIRFlags.

5. Conclusion:
The crash is due to attribute-insensitive equality for commutative intrinsics in EarlyCSE, violating an internal invariant relied upon later. Adding an attribute intersection feasibility check to the commutative intrinsic equality path prevents misclassification and resolves the abort without weakening correctness. After this fix EarlyCSE will refuse to CSE such mismatched calls, and combineIRFlags will no longer encounter impossible attribute intersections.
